The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                 NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 New Delhi, March 26: The Centre today launched a nationwide health insurance scheme for people suffering from mental handicaps like autism and cerebral palsy or from multiple disabilities. Called Niramaya (disease-free), the scheme will first target one lakh Below Poverty Line card-holders who suffer from these conditions and include any surgery that might be required. The government will pay the entire premium for a health insurance up to Rs 1 lakh a person.           
	Those suffering from autism, cerebral palsy and other mental handicaps, or suffering from multiple disabilities  like those who are both deaf and visually impaired  will be covered by the scheme, Meira Kumar, the minister for social justice and empowerment, said. People with special needs seeking health insurance are often rejected by companies, government officials said, explaining the need for the scheme.                   
	Jammu (PTI): An army jawan was shot dead on Tuesday by a security guard at a camp in Kargil. The guard mistook Naik Ramesh Kumar to be an intruder as he was wrapped in a blanket and refused to stop when the guard asked him to.                   
	 Hyderabad (PTI): A Telugu NRI, who had come to India from the US on a business trip, was found dead yesterday in his hotel room at Banjara Hills. Police have found a white powder-like substance on Anand Pavan Kumars bed. It has been sent for forensic test.                   
	Pune (PTI): Pandit Bhimsen Joshi, who was hospitalised two weeks ago after he complained of breathing problems, is improving. The artificial respiratory support was removed on Wednesday as his lungs started functioning properly, Dr N. Yalgi said.                   
	 Thrissur (PTI): A young couple committed suicide by consuming pesticide in a paddy field in nearby Arimpoor on Tuesday. The couple, who have left behind two small children, are believed to have been in debt, police said.                                                                                                                           
